The alternative toxic release scenario at the Franklin Park Plant involves the release of 2,773 pounds of ammonia to the atmosphere over a 31-minute period due to a cracked sight glass on a high-pressure ammonia receiver. The release rate  assumes that the enclosed engine room would limit the amount of ammonia released to the atmosphere. Under alternative release conditions, the resulting vapor cloud could have off-site impacts.

The worst-case and alternative toxic release scenarios are unlikely for the following reasons:

- The weather conditions that were used for the worst-case release scenario do not occur, while those used for the alternative case are uncommon;
- Industry standards are followed for the design and manufacture of the equipment in the ammonia refrigeration system;
- The high pressure ammonia receiver is located in an enclosed engine room, well protected from vehicular traffic;
- Pressure safety valves on the high pressure receiver should limit any pressure increases inside the receiver;
- Ammonia detectors should readily detect releases from the high pressure receiver;
- Ammonia is not corrosive in this service; 
 -The facility has a Preventive Maintenance Program in place to maintain the on-going integrity of the ammonia refrigeration equipment;
- The facility has a Training Program designed to ensure that the systems are operated by qualified personnel; and, 
- The facility's Emergency Response Procedures enable trained personnel to respond quickly to isolate any potential releases.


